result.execSummary:
The defendant Darrin J Kinney was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • 2nd Degree Sexual Assault of Child, a class C felony, Wisconsin Statutes 948.02(2).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

supervisions.notes: Pay Restitution in the amount of $252.99 to D.W.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.  Restitution to be satisfied before the courts, fees, assessments and surcharges.

No fine. Pay the costs, fees, assessments and surcharges during the term of extended supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment. DOC to collect monetary sums/amounts at the rate of 25% of prison funds.

State informs Court that defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration or Substance Abuse program.  
Court advises defendant that in the event State law is changed, Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program, after 40 months of the initial confinement is served.

Consecutive to: with 240 days credit, consecutive to the sentence imposed as to Case# 15CF001812.

superMiscConds.notes: Seek/Maintain full-time employment or a combination of part-time employment and school. Obtain GED/HSD.

No contact with the victim D.W.
No weapons of any kind.

Complete an Anger Mgmnt. program.
Cognitive Behavior Therapy.
Comply with all rules as to the Sex Offender Registry.

records.addlTxt:
Defendant Darrin J Kinney in court with Attorney John Thaddeus Wasielewski.  Defendant Darrin J Kinney in custody.  Jesica Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Defendant has two cases before the court.

Sentencing proceeds.  State has complied with victim notification.  Statements by the State, defense counsel, Shadmeshabed K., and defendant.   COURT ADVISES the defendant he cannot possess firearms, he must provide a DNA sample and cannot vote until his civil rights are restored.  

COURT ORDERS defendant to serve a term in the Wisconsin State Prison system - TOTAL LENGTH OF SENTENCE -  8  years with  240 days credit, consecutive to the sentence imposed as to Case# 15CF001812 -  INITIAL TERM OF CONFINEMENT -  3 years  -  EXTENDED SUPERVISION -  5 years
- Court sets Restitution in the amount of $252.99

State informs Court that defendant is not eligible for the Challenge Incarceration or Substance Abuse program.  
Court advises defendant that in the event State law is changed, Court finds defendant IS eligible for the Challenge Incarceration Program and IS eligible for the Substance Abuse Program, after 40 months of the initial confinement is served.

CONDITIONS OF EXTENDED SUPERVISION:  
-  Complete an Anger Mgmnt. program
-  Cognitive Behavior Therapy
-  Seek/Maintain full-time employment or a combination of part-time employment and school
-  Obtain GED/HSD
-  No contact with the victim D.W.
-  Pay Restitution in the amount of $252.99 to D.W.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.  Restitution to be satisfied before the courts, fees, assessments and surcharges.
-  No weapons of any kind
-  No fine
-  Pay the costs, fees, assessments and surcharges during the term of extended supervision.  Failure to pay will result in a civil judgment.
-  Comply with all rules as to the Sex Offender Registry

COURT ORDERS:
-  defendant to provide a biological specimen for DNA analysis, if not already done so
-  DOC to collect monetary sums/amounts at the rate of 25% of prison funds.

Appeal rights given.  Written Explanation of Determinate Sentence received and filed.  Copies given to the defendant.

Defendant Darrin J Kinney in court with attorney John Thaddeus Wasielewski.  Defendant Darrin J Kinney in custody.  Jesica Ballenger appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Deputy court clerk ccp.
Case set for plea hearing. Parties have reached a resolution in this matter. State placed negotiations on the record. 
Defendant sworn in.

As to COUNT 1-
Defendant was advised of constitutional rights and maximum penalties, waived all rights, and plead GUILTY.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Plea Questionnaire/Waiver of Rights, Addendum, and Jury Instructions received and filed.  Stipulation by parties to the Criminal Complaint as a factual basis to sustain the plea.  Court found the defendant guilty.  Judgment of conviction entered.
  
Court advised defendant that as a convicted felon he may never possess any gun or other firearms. 
Court advised defendant that his voting rights are suspended, and may not vote in any election until his civil rights are restored.  

Court advised defendant if he is not a citizen of the United States of America, that upon a plea of guilty or no contest for this offense, he could be deported, excluded from admission to his country, or denied naturalization under federal law.  
Court advised that the defendant will have to provide a DNA sample, to the Wisconsin State Crime Laboratory for DNA testing and pay a DNA surcharge.

Court advised the defendant that upon a conviction of this offense he may be subject to Chapter 980 proceedings.
Court advised the defendant of the sex offender registry requirements.

Defendant has several pending cases in front of Judge Brash, Branch 21. Parties do not object to this matter be transferred to Branch 21 for purposes of consolidation. 
Court ordered the defendant REMANDED into custody. Case adjourned to Branch 21.  Scheduling conference scheduled for September 11, 2015 at 08:30 am.
